Charlie Chaplin is remembered worldwide for his iconic silent film character The Tramp, instantly recognizable by his bowler hat, cane, oversized shoes, and small toothbrush mustache. Chaplin first introduced the look in 1914, and it became so tied to his image that most audiences never saw him without it. The makeup and costume were carefully chosen â the baggy clothes and mustache made him look older, while the bowler hat and cane added a mix of dignity and comedy.

Outside of the screen, however, Chaplin looked quite different. Born in London in 1889, he had striking features and was considered very handsome in his youth. His off-screen life contrasted sharply with his on-screen persona: while the Tramp struggled with poverty and bad luck, Chaplin was one of the richest and most powerful figures in Hollywood, later becoming a director, composer, and one of cinemaâs earliest global superstars.

When a firefighter attempted to rescue the stranded bird in London, Jessie greeted him not with gratitudeâbut with a sharp, well-timed expletive. Unlike most birds, parrots donât simply mimic soundsâthey learn language-like communication through context, emotional cues, and social reinforcement.

Jessieâs behavior illustrates key aspects of parrot intelligence. Their brain structures mirror those involved in human speech, allowing them to control tone, rhythm, and even emotionally charged responses. Stressful moments, like being stuck or approached by a stranger, can trigger parrots to recall words associated with similar emotional statesâoften the most colorful ones. Though parrots donât fully understand grammar or sentence structure, they are highly attuned to emotional and social feedback. Jessieâs rooftop rant wasnât just comedic goldâit was a real-time example of interspecies communication and a reminder that language doesnât always come from human lips. Sound is a big reason why scary movies feel so intense. Some horror films use super low sounds that you canât really hear, but your body can feelâthese make you feel nervous without knowing why. Creepy music with weird or clashing notes also makes your brain feel uncomfortable. Directors like to make things really quiet and then suddenly blast a loud noise to scare you. Even total silence can be scary, because it makes you tense up and wait for something bad to happen.

Scary movies also use strange or messed-up soundsâlike backward breathing or deep growlsâto make things feel unnatural. They also make normal sounds like footsteps or creaky doors louder and more intense to make you feel like something is nearby. If you ever watch a horror scene with no sound, it usually isnât scary at all. Thatâs how powerful sound isâitâs often what really makes a scene terrifying.
